  }), mdx("h1", null, "TL;DR"), mdx("p", null, "To cook an amazing ", mdx("strong", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "brisket in the oven,"), " all you have to do is season it properly. I used the Standard Texas seasoning - Kosher Salt and Black Pepper. Make sure you thoroughly  season your brisket. Turn your oven on to around 400 degrees and let it come fully up to that temperature before placing your Brisket inside. Get some foil and wrap the entire piece of meat. Once you have wrapped your brisket, place it in the oven and wait until the internal temperature has come up to the famed 200 degrees internal temperature. At that point, the brisket in the oven should now be ready to be pulled. From that point, just let it rest for a couple hours and you\u2019re done! Enjoy!"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("h1", null, "Brisket in the Oven - Getting Started:"), mdx("p", null, "Alright! Let\u2019s get cook some amazing Brisket \u2026 in the OVEN! Woah. Does it have smoke flavor? Nope - BUT it does have all the same consistency as a normal smoked Brisket. A Brisket in the oven does have the same flavor profile - for the most part - and has the potential to really come out great. The one I used for this blog post came out with amazingly crisp and tasty BARK. Not only that, just about every piece of it was incredibly moist.  "), mdx("p", null, mdx("strong", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "How did I get an amazingly tender Brisket in the Oven?")), mdx("p", null, "Simple:"), mdx("ul", null, mdx("li", {
    parentName: "ul"
  }, "Brisket Flat"), mdx("li", {
